Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.50,0:00:08.62,Default,,0,0,0,,This is Meta Hook. OpenZeppelin for the new Solana token standard.\NOne hook, three policies, one signed audit receipt per transfer.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:10.00,0:00:24.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Token-2022 shipped its transfer hook in early 2024.\NBut shipping production compliance still means writing a custom\Nhook per mint, or paying Securitize half a million dollars to wrap\Nyour fund the way BlackRock did. There is no third option.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:26.00,0:00:36.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Until now. I connect Phantom on devnet. One click.\NClick Provision, and a single signed transaction sets up the mint\Nwith both policies wired into the transfer hook.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.50,0:00:45.90,Default,,0,0,0,,Now I send a hundred to a wallet that is not on the allowlist.\NPhantom asks me to confirm. The hook rejects. policy.allowlist.fail.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.00,0:00:52.06,Default,,0,0,0,,I add the wallet to the allowlist with one CPI call.\NThe meta-hook code never moves.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:53.00,0:01:06.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Same transfer fires again. Both policies stamp PASS,\Nand the audit event lands in the program logs, base64-encoded,\Ndecoded right here in the browser. One signed receipt per transfer.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.00,0:01:17.89,Default,,0,0,0,,And it composes. Anyone can fork the spec,\Nship a new policy in 200 lines of Rust,\Nand slot it into a live mint without touching the meta-hook code.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:20.00,0:01:27.75,Default,,0,0,0,,MetaHook. Compose your compliance stack the same way you\Ncompose middleware in Express.\NTry the live demo. The code is on GitHub.
